# Env and ignore file access

- You may read local env files and ignore files when there is a concrete reason.
- Treat this repository as allowing conservative full access to `.env*`,
  `.gitignore`, `.cursorignore`, and similar config files when they are relevant
  to the task.
- Valid reasons include debugging setup, deployment issues, env mismatches,
  integration failures, archive visibility, documentation cleanup, and repo
  structure work.
- This access includes files such as `.env*`, `ENV.md`, `config/env-policy.json`,
  `.gitignore`, `.cursorignore`, `.dockerignore`, `.eslintignore`,
  `.prettierignore`, `.npmignore`, and similar ignore/config files.
- Prefer the smallest useful read first, but do not avoid these files when they
  are the real source of truth for the issue.
- You may edit ignore files when needed to improve project structure, indexing,
  archival visibility, or maintenance workflows.
- You may also edit env files or env-adjacent config when the user explicitly
  wants setup/help with API keys, secrets, or environment wiring, but stay
  conservative and avoid broad unrelated changes.
- Never commit secrets, paste raw secret values into chat, or expose sensitive
  env contents unless the user explicitly asks for the exact values.
- When reporting on env files, summarize keys, categories, or mismatches unless
  full values are necessary and explicitly requested.
